<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-577-842  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 577 842.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  August 24 1989 n1178 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Payroll pays for bureaux. (computer service firms)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Jones, Keith.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Data processing for outside customers once formed the backbone ofthe computer services industry, but no longer.andP;  Inexpensivein-house solutions keep prices down and force service bureaus tolook for other sources of revenue, including training, consultingand providing supplies.andP;  Service bureau revenues are not decliningin absolute terms, however.andP;  Online database services and payrollprocessing are booming.andP;  The market looks good for service bureausthat handle uncommon or infrequent processing tasks or that handletransaction-intensive projects like engineering analysis.andP;  Forexample, one firm links 5,000 financial advisors across England toits insurance quotation service.andP;  Firms with complex payrollapplications that cannot be executed by a microcomputer packageoften go to a computer bureau, as do firms seeking greaterconfidentiality.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Service BureausIndustry AnalysisComputer ServicesPayrollFinancial Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>